---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Icon from '../components/Icon.astro';
const title = "Insights - SubZeroSec";
const description = "Original writing on attack paths, engagements, and offensive security strategy.";
---
<Base title={title} description={description} active="insights">
<section class="phead">
  <div class="phbg" aria-hidden="true"></div>
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="crumb"><a href="index.html">Home</a> <i>/</i> <span>Insights</span></div><span class="eyebrow">INSIGHTS</span>
    <h1>Field notes from the offense.</h1>
    <p class="lead">Original writing on attack paths, engagements, and the economics of getting breached - from the people who run the attacks.</p>
  </div>
</section>
<section class="sec light cutA"><div class="geo" aria-hidden="true"></div><div class="wrap"><a class="feature" href="insight-why-most-zero-days-start-as-forgotten-assets.html"><div class="fthumb"><span class="cat">Attack Surface</span></div><div class="fbody"><div class="meta">Bilal Khan &middot; 12 May 2026 &middot; 6 min read</div><h3>Why most zero-days start as forgotten assets</h3><p>The dangerous part of an unknown asset is not that it is vulnerable. It is that no one is watching it long enough to notice when it becomes a problem.</p><span class="lm">Read article <Icon name="arrow-right" /></span></div></a><div class="posts" style="margin-top:1.4rem"><a class="post" href="insight-red-team-vs-penetration-test-choosing-the-right-engagement.html"><div class="thumb"><span class="cat">Engagements</span></div><div class="pb"><div class="meta">3 Apr 2026 &middot; 7 min read</div><h3>Red team vs penetration test: choosing the right engagement</h3><p>They are not the same service at different price points. They answer different questions, and buying the wrong one wastes a real opportunity.</p></div></a><a class="post" href="insight-the-economics-of-an-attack-path.html"><div class="thumb"><span class="cat">Strategy</span></div><div class="pb"><div class="meta">18 Feb 2026 &middot; 6 min read</div><h3>The economics of an attack path</h3><p>Attackers are rational actors with budgets. Understanding their cost model tells you which defenses actually change their behavior.</p></div></a><a class="post" href="insight-attack-surface-management-for-cloud-native-teams.html"><div class="thumb"><span class="cat">Cloud Security</span></div><div class="pb"><div class="meta">9 Jan 2026 &middot; 7 min read</div><h3>Attack surface management for cloud-native teams</h3><p>In a cloud-native estate, the attack surface is defined by code, changes every deploy, and is owned by everyone. Old inventory habits cannot keep up.</p></div></a><a class="post" href="insight-beyond-the-cve-why-context-decides-risk.html"><div class="thumb"><span class="cat">Vulnerability Management</span></div><div class="pb"><div class="meta">20 Nov 2025 &middot; 6 min read</div><h3>Beyond the CVE: why context decides risk</h3><p>A CVSS score describes a vulnerability in a vacuum. Risk lives in the context the score throws away - where the asset sits and what it guards.</p></div></a></div></div></section>
<section class="sec light cutC"><div class="geo" aria-hidden="true"></div><div class="wrap"><div class="cta-in"><span class="eyebrow">Get ahead of zero</span><h2>Ready to see yourself the way an <span class="r">adversary would?</span></h2><p>Book a scoped assessment - we will map what is reachable, prove what is exploitable, and give you a ranked path to closing it before someone finds it first.</p><a href="contact.html" class="btn btn-fill">Book a free scoping call <Icon name="arrow-right" /></a></div></div></section>
</Base>
